Theatre music refers wide range music composed adapted for performance theatres Genres theatre music include opera ballet and several forms musical theatre from pantomime operetta and modern stage musicals and revues Another form theatre music incidental music which radio film and television used accompany the action separate the scenes play The physical embodiment the music called score which includes the music and there are lyrics also shows the lyrics Since the earliest days the theatre music has played important part stage drama Greek drama the fifth century choric odes were written chanted and danced between the spoken sections both tragedies and comedies Only fragments the music have survived Attempts recreate the form for revivals from the Renaissance modern times have branched several directions Composers from Andrea Gabrieli Mendelssohn Vaughan Williams have composed chorus music for productions plays Sophocles Aristophanes and others Playwrights including Racine Yeats and Brecht wrote original plays styles derived from ancient drama with sung commentaries chorus narrator late 16th century Florence attempts revive ancient Greek drama with sung vocal contributions developed into the modern genre opera Folk theatre has always deployed dance music and song the 16th and 17th centuries theatre music was performed during the action plays and afterpieces Christopher Wilson discussing Shakespeares use music lists stage music fanfares introduce important characters accompany battle scenes magic music the lullaby Midsummer Nights Dream character music Twelfth Night illustrating the high low sad merry natures the characters and atmospheric music such Ariels Where the bee sucks The Tempest the early 18th century music was firmly established part practically all theatrical performances Europe whether opera dance spoken drama Theatres were built with orchestra pits and music was either specially composed for the production appropriated and arranged from existing material